DNS Server Configuration in Windows Server
Definition

DNS (Domain Name System) converts:

Domain names → IP addresses
Example:

company.local → 192.168.1.10


DNS is required for Active Directory, domain login, and network services.

Requirement

Windows Server installed

Static IP configured on server

Active Directory Domain Services installed

Logged in as Domain Administrator

Example Used
Domain Name: company.local
DNS Server IP: 192.168.1.10
Server Name: DC01

PART 1: Install DNS Server Role
Step 1: Open Server Manager

Login to Windows Server

Open Server Manager

Step 2: Add Roles and Features

Click Manage

Select Add Roles and Features

Click Next

Select Role-based or feature-based installation

Click Next

Select Local Server

Click Next

Step 3: Select DNS Server

Select DNS Server

Click Add Features

Click Next

Click Install

PART 2: Open DNS Manager
Step 1: Open DNS Console

Open Server Manager

Click Tools

Select DNS

PART 3: Verify Forward Lookup Zone

When AD is installed, DNS zone is created automatically

Step 1: Check Forward Lookup Zone

Expand DNS

Expand Server Name

Expand Forward Lookup Zones

Confirm zone exists:

company.local

PART 4: Create New Forward Lookup Zone (If Not Exists)
Step 1: Create Zone

Right-click Forward Lookup Zones

Click New Zone

Click Next

Select Primary Zone

Check Store the zone in Active Directory

Click Next

Step 2: Zone Name

Enter:

company.local


Click Next

Step 3: Dynamic Update

Select:

Allow only secure dynamic updates


Click Next

Click Finish

PART 5: Create Host (A) Record
Step 1: Create A Record

Open company.local

Right-click → New Host (A or AAAA)

Step 2: Enter Details
Name: server1
IP Address: 192.168.1.10


Check Create associated PTR record

Click Add Host

Click OK

PART 6: Reverse Lookup Zone
Step 1: Create Reverse Lookup Zone

Right-click Reverse Lookup Zones

Click New Zone

Click Next

Select Primary Zone

Click Next

Select IPv4 Reverse Lookup Zone

Click Next

Step 2: Network ID
Network ID: 192.168.1


Click Next

Allow secure dynamic updates

Click Finish

PART 7: Configure Client DNS Settings
On Client Machine

Open Network Adapter Settings

Open IPv4 Properties

Set Preferred DNS Server:

192.168.1.10


Click OK

PART 8: Verify DNS Working
Using Command Prompt
ipconfig /all
nslookup company.local
ping company.local

Verification

Domain name resolves to IP

Client can join domain

Domain login works properly

Common DNS Commands
ipconfig /flushdns
ipconfig /registerdns
nslookup

Conclusion

DNS Server has been successfully installed and configured.
DNS is now supporting Active Directory, DHCP, and domain login operations.
